text:
@LutonTown 3 Cardiff City 0 in Division 2 (now the Championship) at Kenilworth Road on August 30, 1948.
South African-born Billy Arnison scored a hat-trick in only his 4th game for the Hatters.
Attendance: 20,185. https://t.co/8yMZtiBodX

@Rovers Another addition to the list of too-big-for-their-boots Championship clubs who "should be beating teams like Luton".
When was the last time @Rovers won @LutonTown in a League game?
#teamslikeluton

@daveflettpress @LutonTown The Town have a superb record in Yorkshire.
They've already played at Rotherham, Sheffield Wednesday, Barnsley and Huddersfield this season, picking up 10 points out of 12.
Good results last season included wins at Barnsley and Huddersfield and a draw at Leeds.

@nickowentv @BrentfordFC Not the first time winged creatures have swapped leagues.
Last season, the Canaries of Norwich City replaced the Bluebirds of Cardiff City, a year after the Bluebirds had taken the place of the Swans of Swansea City.
In 1994 the Eagles of Palace replaced the Robins of Swindon.

@LutonNews_LTFC I've had a shocker.
38th and only three correct scores.
In the old days the league would have asked me to apply for re-election.

@double0kmp @Yorktone I think he's had a bad day,
I think he's had a bad season,
Thinking about it, he's had quite a few bad seasons.

@LutonTown v Hull City in Div 2 (now Championship) in front of packed Kenilworth Rd standing terrace 1973.
Scoreboard told fans half-time and full-time scores in other games in days before mobile phones.
A code for each letter and the match it related to was printed in programme. https://t.co/9f9J1TyS9t

Old Luton pictures (continued):
@LutonTown home match at Kenilworth Road in 1907 - two years after the club moved there.
View from the Main Stand, with the Oak Road End behind the goal. https://t.co/MQSeoU4VNY

Championship average away attendances this season.
@LutonTown 8th out of 24.
Terrific support for the Hatters on the road, as usual. https://t.co/aMcJ4gN7CM

@LutonTown love beating 'B' teams this season.
There are five of them in the Championship and the Hatters have already defeated Barnsley, Blackburn Rovers and Bristol City.
Hopefully they can complete the set with wins against Birmingham City on Saturday and Brentford on Nov 30.

@LutonTown v @HullCity in Div 2 (now Championship) at Kenilworth Road, October 27, 1973.
The game, watched by 11,408, ended 2-2. Town's scorers were Peter Anderson/Barry Butlin.
Promotion was gained to top flight at end of that season, with Hatters runners-up to Middlesbrough. https://t.co/EcV1xj7DRz

@LutonTown and @LCFC have met 63 times in all competitions, but not for the past 12 years.
They have played each other in the League Cup just the once, in 1984 when the Hatters won 3-1.
Luton's complete record against Leicester is W19 D21 L23.

@LutonTown play WBA in the Championship at Kenilworth Road tomorrow and I've predicted a 1-1 score.
That was the result when the two teams met on the Hatters' home ground in Division Two (now the Championship) on September 13, 1947.
Here's an action shot from that game. https://t.co/r2oLypTyOm

Walked dog, made cup of coffee and then turned on TV to watch final day of 1st Test in latest Ashes series.
First thing I spotted as Aussie ran in to bowl was a large flag in background at Edgbaston.
@LutonTown fans - they're here, they're there, they're every ****ingwhere. https://t.co/dKVxEB2ltB

@LutonTown have beaten 30-year-old transfer record and we wish keeper Simon Sluga well.
But we'll never forget the Hatters' first 'Croatian sensation', who was at the club from 2001-2008 and played more than 200 games.
Ahmet Brkovic in pre-season training during that period. https://t.co/UIr0TSQQ04

@lutontown players with the club's new car in 1959 - the year the Hatters reached the FA Cup final.
Pictured with the vehicle in Kenilworth Road are (l to r) Syd Owen, Billy Bingham, Ron Baynham and Allan Brown.
All four played in the Wembley final against Nottingham Forest. https://t.co/0tkqD36nCp

It's always good to get a home draw against lower league opposition in the cup competitions.
@LutonTown v @IpswichTown 
#CarabaoCup

@lutontown started the 2013-14 season with games against Southport, Salisbury and Macclesfield.
The Hatters begin the 2019-20 season 3 tiers higher in the football pyramid with matches against Middlesbrough, Cardiff City and WBA.
We've come a very long way in such a short time.

@LutonTownExile @LutonTown I saw Zlatan Ibrahimovich playing for Ajax against @LutonTown in a pre-season friendly.
Also saw Bobby Moore for Fulham v Hatters.
A bit before my time, but Sir Stanley Matthews played at Kenilworth Road as well.

@LutonTown 2 Hull City 2 with Kenilworth Road End (open standing terrace and old-fashioned scoreboard) in background on October 27, 1973.
Hatters promoted to Division One (now Premier League) that season, runners-up to Middlesbrough.
Alan West on the ball passing to John Aston. https://t.co/jCz0jGQicF

@SunderlandAFC, the club too big for its boots. Arrogant fans shown today that you have no divine right to win anything in this game.
A £4million striker on fire at his previous club, but a damp squib against @CAFCofficial.
#CHASUN #LeagueOnePlayoffFinal

Former @LutonTown manager Nathan Jones missed out on a League One title after he cleared off mid-season, but he achieved one record.
@stokecity drew 22 league games, the most ever by a team in a second-tier campaign.
Not much of a consolation prize for the Welsh weasel, is it?

Disgraceful that a game in the third tier of English football is being played on a pitch that looks like a farmer's ploughed field.
And don't tell me it's the same for both teams.
@lutontown

